**Sec. 70401**
This section increases the employer-provided child care credit percentage from 25 percent to 40 percent, or 50 percent for eligible small businesses defined by a 5-year gross receipts test. The maximum credit amount is raised to $500,000 generally, or $600,000 for eligible small businesses, with these limits subject to inflation adjustments starting in 2027. The law now allows credits for services provided through third-party intermediaries and clarifies that jointly owned or operated facilities qualify. These changes apply to amounts paid or incurred after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70402**
This section makes up to $5,000 of the adoption credit refundable, allowing taxpayers to receive the credit even if they owe no tax. It permanently adjusts the credit dollar amounts for inflation using a 2001 base year, with rounding to the nearest $10. Additionally, the refundable portion is excluded from the calculation of carryforwards for the non-refundable portion of the credit. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70403**
This amendment modifies the definition of "special needs" for the adoption credit to explicitly include determinations made by Indian tribal governments, not just State governments. This change ensures that children adopted from tribal foster care systems are treated consistently with those adopted from State systems for credit eligibility. The provision applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70404**
This section increases the maximum amount of dependent care assistance that can be excluded from an employee's gross income under the Dependent Care Assistance Program from $5,000 to $7,500 ($3,750 for married individuals filing separately). This enhancement aims to provide greater tax relief for families utilizing employer-sponsored dependent care benefits. The increase applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70405**
This provision significantly increases the maximum applicable percentage for the child and dependent care tax credit to 50 percent for taxpayers with adjusted gross income (AGI) up to $15,000. The credit percentage phases down by 1 percentage point for every $2,000 of AGI above $15,000, but not below 35 percent, and further reduces to a floor of 20 percent for AGI exceeding $75,000 ($150,000 for joint filers). These changes are designed to expand the credit's value for middle-income families. The amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70411**
This section creates a new non-refundable tax credit of up to $1,700 for individuals who make qualified cash contributions to state-verified scholarship granting organizations for elementary and secondary education. The credit is reduced by any state tax credit claimed for the same contributions and is limited to contributions used for students in households with income not exceeding 300 percent of the area median gross income. Scholarship organizations must spend at least 90 percent of their income on these scholarships and cannot earmark funds for specific students. The credit and the corresponding exclusion from gross income for scholarships apply to taxable years ending after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70412**
This section makes the exclusion for employer payments of up to $5,250 toward an employee's student loan debt permanent, removing the previous expiration date of January 1, 2026. The $5,250 limit is subject to inflation adjustments starting in 2027, with increases rounded to the nearest $50. This change applies to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70413**
This section expands the definition of qualified higher education expenses for 529 plans to include tuition, curriculum, books, online materials, and specific tutoring fees for elementary and secondary school students. It also increases the annual limit on contributions to 529 plans for a designated beneficiary from $10,000 to $20,000. The expansion of qualified expenses applies to distributions made after the date of enactment, while the contribution limit increase applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70414**
This provision allows 529 account distributions to be used tax-free for qualified postsecondary credentialing expenses, including tuition, fees, books, and testing fees for recognized industry credentials. Recognized credentials include those accredited by the Institute for Credentialing Excellence, listed in the Department of Defense's COOL directory, or registered apprenticeships. The definition of qualified expenses now explicitly covers these non-degree programs to support workforce development. These amendments apply to distributions made after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70415**
This section modifies the excise tax on investment income for private colleges and universities, imposing a tiered tax rate of 1.4 percent, 4 percent, or 8 percent based on the institution's student-adjusted endowment per student. The tax applies to institutions with at least 3,000 tuition-paying students and a student-adjusted endowment exceeding $500,000, with rates increasing as the endowment per student rises above $750,000 and $2,000,000. The definition of net investment income is expanded to include interest from student loans and federally-subsidized royalty income. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70416**
This amendment expands the definition of "covered employee" for the 21 percent excise tax on excess compensation at tax-exempt organizations to include any former employee who worked for the organization in any taxable year beginning after December 31, 2016. Previously, the definition was limited to current employees and those who were covered employees in the preceding year. This change ensures that compensation paid to former high-earning employees remains subject to the tax. The amendment applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70421**
This section permanently renews Opportunity Zones with a new decennial designation cycle starting July 1, 2026, and repeals the special rule allowing Puerto Rico to have additional designations. It updates the definition of low-income communities to include census tracts with poverty rates of at least 20 percent and median family income below 125 percent of the area median. The section introduces a new "qualified rural opportunity fund" category offering a 30 percent basis increase for investments held for 5 years in rural areas. New reporting requirements are established for funds and businesses, and the tax on capital gains deferral is modified to include a 30-year holding period for basis step-up.

**Sec. 70422**
This section permanently increases the Low-Income Housing Tax Credit (LIHTC) ceiling multiplier from 1.125 to 1.12 for calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025, effectively adjusting the credit calculation for new allocations. It also modifies the tax-exempt bond financing requirement, allowing the credit to be claimed even if 25 percent or more of the building's basis is financed by tax-exempt bonds, provided the bonds were issued after December 31, 2025, and finance at least 5 percent of the basis. These changes aim to facilitate more affordable housing development through flexible financing. The amendments apply to buildings placed in service in taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70423**
This section permanently extends the New Markets Tax Credit (NMTC) allocation authority for each calendar year after 2019, removing the previous sunset date of 2025. It also clarifies that unused allocation limitations can be carried forward for up to five years, with any excess from years before 2026 treated as occurring in 2025. This ensures continued federal support for community development projects in low-income areas. The amendments apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70424**
This section permanently reinstates and expands the above-the-line deduction for charitable contributions for individuals who do not itemize, increasing the limit from $300 ($600 for joint filers) to $1,000 ($2,000 for joint filers). The provision removes the temporary expiration date, making the deduction a permanent feature of the tax code for non-itemizers. This change provides tax relief to a broader range of taxpayers making charitable donations. The amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70425**
This section imposes a 0.5 percent floor on the deduction of charitable contributions for individuals, meaning contributions are only deductible to the extent they exceed 0.5 percent of the taxpayer's contribution base. The floor applies in a specific order, prioritizing contributions to certain organizations before applying to others, and allows disallowed amounts to be carried forward for up to five years. This change is intended to limit the tax benefit of small charitable donations while preserving the deduction for larger contributions. The amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70426**
This section imposes a 1 percent floor on the deduction of charitable contributions for corporations, allowing deductions only for contributions that exceed 1 percent of taxable income, while maintaining the existing 10 percent overall limit. It also clarifies that contributions disallowed due to the 10 percent limit can be carried forward for up to five years, but contributions disallowed solely by the 1 percent floor are not carried forward unless the 10 percent limit is exceeded. This change adjusts the deduction rules to ensure corporations contribute a minimum threshold before receiving tax benefits. The amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70427**
This section permanently increases the limitation on the amount of tax that can be covered over for distilled spirits from the previous amount to $13.25. This adjustment applies to distilled spirits brought into the United States after December 31, 2025. The change ensures the tax coverage limit keeps pace with economic factors.

**Sec. 70428**
This section clarifies that nonprofit community development activities related to fisheries in the Bering Sea and Aleutian Islands are substantially related to the exempt purpose of entities identified under the Magnuson-Stevens Act. It allows for the tax-free transfer of assets from wholly owned subsidiaries engaged in these activities to the parent nonprofit entity within 18 months of enactment. This provision supports the economic viability of remote Native Alaskan villages through the fishing industry. The section takes effect on the date of enactment and remains effective as long as the western Alaska community development quota program exists.

**Sec. 70429**
This section increases the limit on the charitable deduction for expenses incurred in support of Native Alaskan subsistence whaling from $10,000 to $50,000. This adjustment allows individuals to deduct a higher amount of expenses related to this specific cultural and subsistence activity. The change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70430**
This section expands the exception to the percentage of completion method of accounting to include all residential construction contracts, not just home construction contracts, and extends the look-back period for the exception from 2 years to 3 years. It also clarifies that this exception applies for purposes of the Alternative Minimum Tax. This change simplifies accounting for residential builders and reduces compliance burdens. The amendments apply to contracts entered into in taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70431**
This section phases in an increase in the exclusion for gain from the sale of qualified small business stock, raising the exclusion percentage to 50 percent for stock held 3 years, 75 percent for 4 years, and 100 percent for 5 years or more. It also increases the per-issuer limitation on eligible gain from $10 million to $15 million for stock acquired after the date of enactment, with the $10 million limit remaining for stock acquired before that date. The aggregate gross assets limit for qualifying corporations is raised from $50 million to $75 million. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70432**
This section repeals the American Rescue Plan Act's reduction of the de minimis reporting threshold for third-party network transactions, reinstating the requirement to report only if transactions exceed $20,000 and 200 payments. It also applies this de minimis rule to backup withholding, meaning payments are reportable only if the aggregate transactions exceed the $20,000 and 200 thresholds. This change reduces reporting burdens for payment settlement organizations and payees with low-volume transactions. The reinstatement applies as if included in the original legislation, and the backup withholding rule applies to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70433**
This section increases the threshold for requiring information reporting on payments to payees from $600 to $2,000, applying to payments made after December 31, 2025. The $2,000 threshold is subject to inflation adjustments starting in 2026, rounded to the nearest $100. This change reduces the administrative burden on businesses for reporting small payments. The amendments apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70434**
This section expands the immediate expensing rules under Section 181 to include qualified sound recording productions, allowing up to $150,000 of costs to be deducted in the year incurred. It also allows qualified sound recording productions to be treated as qualified property for bonus depreciation purposes. A sound recording production is defined as a recording produced and recorded in the United States. These amendments apply to productions commencing in taxable years ending after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70435**
This section creates a new exclusion from gross income for 25 percent of interest received by qualified lenders on loans secured by rural or agricultural real estate. Qualified lenders include banks, insurance companies, and certain federally chartered instrumentalities, while the loans must be secured by property used for agriculture, fishing, or aquaculture. This provision aims to lower borrowing costs and stimulate investment in rural and agricultural sectors. The exclusion applies to taxable years ending after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70436**
This section reduces the transfer and manufacturing excise taxes on firearms to $0 for most firearms, maintaining a $200 tax only for machineguns and destructive devices. The change effectively eliminates the tax on standard firearms while keeping the tax on regulated weapons. This reduction applies to calendar quarters beginning more than 90 days after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70437**
This section allows taxpayers selling qualified farmland to a qualified farmer to elect to pay the resulting net income tax in four equal installments over four years. To qualify, the property must have been used as a farm for the preceding 10 years and must be subject to a restriction preventing non-farm use for 10 years after the sale. This provision helps farmers manage the tax burden of selling land to ensure it remains in agricultural use. The election applies to sales or exchanges in taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70438**
This section extends the rules for the treatment of certain disaster-related personal casualty losses by substituting the date of enactment for the original enactment date in the relevant provisions of the Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Tax Relief Act of 2020. This ensures that the disaster relief provisions remain applicable to losses occurring after the original expiration. The extension applies to losses incurred in taxable years following the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70439**
This section restores the taxable REIT subsidiary asset test limit from 20 percent back to 25 percent, allowing REITs to hold a larger portion of their assets in taxable REIT subsidiaries. This change provides REITs with more flexibility in structuring their operations and investments. The amendment applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025. [end of text]


